3.20

Computational Caustics

Mark Pauly (EPFL â Lausanne, CH)
License Joint work of Main reference URL URL

Creative Commons BY 3.0 Unported license Â© Mark Pauly Pauly, Mark; Yuliy Schwartzburg, Romain Testuz, Andrea Tagliasacchi Y. Schwartzburg, R. Testuz, A. Tagliasacchi, M. Pauly, âHigh-contrast Computational Caustic Design,â ACM Trans. on Graphics, 33(4):74, 2014. http://dx.doi.org/10.1145/2601097.2601200 http://lgg.epï¬.ch/publications/2014/HighContrastCaustics.pdf

We present a new algorithm for computational caustic design. Our algorithm solves for the shape of a transparent object such that the re- fracted light paints a desired caustic image on a receiver screen. We introduce an optimal transport formulation to establish a correspon- dence between the input geometry and the unknown target shape. A subsequent 3D optimization based on an adaptive discretization scheme then ï¬nds the target surface from the correspondence map. Our approach supports piecewise smooth surfaces and non-bijective mappings, which eliminates a number of shortcomings of previous methods. This leads to a signiï¬cantly richer space of caustic images, including smooth transitions, singularities of inï¬nite light density, and completely black areas. We demonstrate the eï¬ectiveness of our approach with several simulated and fabricated examples.

