3.25

Use the winding number to determine âinsideâ and âoutsideâ for each level in layered manufacturing

Carlo H. Sequin (University of California â Berkeley, US)
License

Creative Commons BY 3.0 Unported license Â© Carlo H. Sequin

Models of trusses consisting of many joining or intersecting beams, often with non-trivial cross sections, may result in a solid model that does not have a proper, oriented, 2-manifold boundary representation. Cleaning up such a 3D model is laborious and diï¬cult, even when the individual components (beams) themselves have perfectly good B-Reps. Sending such âuncleanâ models to a layered manufacturing machine will often produce unexpected result â or will simply be refused by the machineâs software. This problem could easily be remedied by slicing all components individually, paying careful attention to the orientation of the surface normals, and then forming the Boolean union of all the extracted slicing contours on each level while summing up their respective winding numbers.

